<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="258" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,1328]" pageId="5" pageNumber="258">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1124,1149]" pageId="5" pageNumber="258">Comments.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Lima, 2018" authorityName="Lima" authorityYear="2018" box="[345,633,1124,1149]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Simothraulopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="258" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sinuosus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[345,633,1124,1149]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="258">Simothraulopsis sinuosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[643,736,1124,1149]" pageId="5" pageNumber="258" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[643,736,1124,1149]" pageId="5" pageNumber="258">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
has a color pattern very similar to that of 
<taxonomicName authority="Mariano, 2010" authorityName="Mariano" authorityYear="2010" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Simothraulopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="258" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="diamantinensis">
<emphasis box="[1235,1436,1124,1149]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="258">S. diamantinensis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[151,322,1159,1184]" pageId="5" pageNumber="258" refId="ref2721" refString="Mariano, R. (2010) Two new species of Simothraulopsis Traver, 1947 (Ephemeroptera: Leptophlebiidae: Atalophlebiinae) from northeastern Brazil. Aquatic Insects, 32, 129 - 134. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 01650420903393842" type="journal article">Mariano, 2010</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, and additionally, the inner margins of penis lobes are equally divergent, with each lobe almost pointed apically. However, it is clearly distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mariano" authorityYear="2010" box="[807,1005,1196,1221]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Simothraulopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="258" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="diamantinensis">
<emphasis box="[807,1005,1196,1221]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="258">S. diamantinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and others species of the genus by the presence of a peculiar sinuous median size penis projection, while in other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Demoulin" authorityYear="1966" box="[1003,1184,1231,1256]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Simothraulopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="258" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1003,1184,1231,1256]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="258">Simothraulopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species the spines are straight and sometimes a little curved. Besides, the new species has a medial shallow concavity between the penis lobes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
